{
  "Idea": "We propose 'Dynamically Coupled Spatial-Frequency Diffusion Models with Iterative Cross-Domain Fusion' (DCSF-Diffuse), a novel diffusion-based architecture for low-light image restoration that fundamentally rethinks how spatial and frequency information interact during the denoising process. Unlike existing methods that treat these domains separately or fuse them statically, DCSF-Diffuse introduces a dual-branch U-Net-like diffusion backbone—one operating in the spatial domain, the other in the frequency domain (via Fast Fourier Convolutions)—that communicate through a series of iterative cross-domain fusion (ICDF) blocks. Each ICDF block employs a learnable gating mechanism conditioned on both spatial texture gradients and spectral magnitude distributions, enabling context-aware feature modulation across domains. At each denoising timestep, spatial features inform phase correction in the frequency branch, while frequency-domain amplitude maps guide edge-preserving smoothing in the spatial decoder. Additionally, we design a multi-scale pyramid diffusion scheme where the model first restores the image at a coarse scale to recover global illumination and structure, then progressively refines details at higher resolutions. This avoids checkerboard artifacts and ensures smooth transitions. To further stabilize training and improve frequency consistency, we introduce a spectral regularization loss that penalizes deviations from natural image statistics in the frequency domain (e.g., 1/f power law). We also augment training data using a modified CutFreq-inspired strategy, swapping high-frequency components between well-lit and low-light image pairs to encourage robustness to noise-texture confusion. The proposed model is evaluated on LOL, LOLv2, SID, and ExDark datasets, showing superior performance in both quantitative metrics (PSNR, SSIM, LPIPS) and qualitative realism. By unifying dynamic cross-domain interaction, multi-scale progression, and frequency-aware regularization, DCSF-Diffuse sets a new paradigm for physics-informed, perception-driven low-light restoration within the diffusion modeling framework.",
